<article id=3D"content" role=3D"main">

<!-- #BeginEditable "Body" -->=20

<div class=3D"video"><a><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/images/style=
/video.svg" alt=3D"Video" style=3D"width:56px; height:49px;vertical-align:m=
iddle; border:none;"></a><span id=3D"video0" style=3D""></span></div>
<h1 class=3D"center">Intervals</h1>=20


<div class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/sets/images/sa=
ge-interval.avif" alt=3D"sage on an interval" height=3D"215" width=3D"478">=
</div>

<p class=3D"center larger">Interval: all the numbers between two given numb=
ers.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<p>Example: all the numbers between 1 and 6 is an <b>interval</b></p>=20
	</div>


<h2>All The Numbers?</h2>=20

<p>Yes. All the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/real-numbers.=
html">Real Numbers</a> that lie between those 2 values.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: the interval 2 to 4 includes numbers such as:</h3><br>


	<div class=3D"center large">=20
	<div class=3D"box">2,1</div>

<div class=3D"box">2,1111</div>

<div class=3D"box">2,5</div>

<div class=3D"box">2,75</div>

<div class=3D"box">2,80001</div>

<div class=3D"box"><span class=3D"times">=CF=80</span></div>

<div class=3D"box"><span class=3D"f"><u>7</u><em>2</em></span></div>

<div class=3D"box">3,7937</div>
</div>=20

<p>And lots more!</p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Including the Numbers at Each End?</h2>=20

<p>Ahh ... maybe yes, maybe no ... we need to say!</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: "boxes up to 20 kg in mass are allowed"</h3>=20

	<p>If your box is <b>exactly 20 kg</b> ... will that be allowed or not?</p=
>=20
	<p>It isn't really clear.</p>=20
	</div>
<p>Let's see how to be precise about this in each of three popular methods:=
</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>Inequalities</li>=20
	<li>The Number Line</li>=20
	<li>Interval Notation</li>=20
</ul>=20


<h2>Inequalities</h2>=20

<p>With <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/inequality.html">Ineq=
ualities</a> we use:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li><span class=3D"large">&gt;</span> greater than</li>=20
	<li><span class=3D"large">=E2=89=A5</span> greater than or equal to</li>=
=20
	<li><span class=3D"large">&lt;</span> less than</li>=20
	<li><span class=3D"large">=E2=89=A4</span> less than or equal to</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>Like this:</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: <span class=3D"large">x =E2=89=A4 20</span></h3>=20

	<p>Says: "x less than or equal to 20"</p>=20
	<p>And means: up to <b>and including</b> 20</p>=20
	</div>


<h2>Interval Notation</h2>=20

<p>In "Interval Notation" we just write the beginning and ending numbers of=
 the interval, and use:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li><span class=3D"large"> [ ]</span> a square bracket when we want to <b>=
include</b> the end value, or</li>=20
	<li><span class=3D"large">( )</span> a round bracket when we <b>don't</b><=
/li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>Like this:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/sets/images/inte=
rval-notation.svg" alt=3D"Interval Notation" height=3D"169" width=3D"314"><=
/p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: (5, 12]</h3>=20

	<p>Means from 5 to 12, do <b>not</b> include 5, but <b>do</b> include 12</=
p>=20
	</div>


<h2>Number Line</h2>=20

<p>With the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/number-line.html">Number =
Line</a> we draw a thick line to show the values we are including, and:</p>=
=20
<ul>=20
	<li>a filled-in circle when we want to include the end value, or</li>=20
	<li>an open circle when we don't</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>Like this:</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<p>Example:</p>=20
	<div class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/sets/images/i=
nterval-0-20.svg" alt=3D"(0, 20)" height=3D"52" width=3D"241"></div>
<p>means all the numbers between 0 and 20, do <b>not</b> include 0, but <b>=
do</b> include 20</p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"gap"></div>


<h2>All Three Methods Together</h2>=20

<p>Here is a handy table showing all 3 methods (the interval is 1 to 2):</p=
>=20
<div class=3D"simple">

	<table class=3D"center">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td class=3D"wideOnly">&nbsp;</td>
			<td colspan=3D"2" class=3D"large">From 1</td>
			<td colspan=3D"2" class=3D"large">To 2</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"wideOnly">&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">Including 1</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>Not</b> Including 1</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><b>Not</b> Including 2</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"> Including 2</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"large wideOnly">Inequality:</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><span class=3D"large">x =E2=89=A5 1</sp=
an><br>
"greater than<br>
or equal to"</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><span class=3D"large">x &gt; 1</span><b=
r>
"greater than"<br>
&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><span class=3D"large">x &lt; 2</span><b=
r>
"less than"<br>
&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><span class=3D"large">x =E2=89=A4 2</sp=
an><br>
"less than<br>
or equal to"</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"large wideOnly">Number line:</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/=
sets/images/interval-ge-1.svg" alt=3D"=E2=89=A51" height=3D"55" width=3D"70=
"></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/=
sets/images/interval-gt-1.svg" alt=3D"&gt;1" height=3D"55" width=3D"70"></t=
d>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/=
sets/images/interval-lt-2.svg" alt=3D"&lt;2" height=3D"55" width=3D"70"></t=
d>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/=
sets/images/interval-le-2.svg" alt=3D"=E2=89=A42" height=3D"55" width=3D"70=
"></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"large wideOnly">Interval notation:</td>
			<td class=3D"large">[1</td>
			<td class=3D"large">(1</td>
			<td class=3D"large">2)</td>
			<td class=3D"large">2]</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"gap"></div>
<p>Example: to <b>include 1</b>, and <b>not include 2</b>:</p>=20
<div class=3D"simple">

	<table class=3D"center" style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td class=3D"large">Inequality:</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">=20
<p><span class=3D"large">x =E2=89=A5 1</span> and <span class=3D"large">x &=
lt; 2</span><br>
or together: <span class=3D"large">1 </span><span class=3D"large">=E2=89=A4=
</span><span class=3D"large"> x &lt; 2</span><br></p></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"large">Number line:</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/=
sets/images/interval-ge-1.svg" alt=3D"&gt;1" height=3D"55" width=3D"70"><im=
g src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/sets/images/interval-lt-2.svg" alt=3D"&=
lt;2" height=3D"55" width=3D"70"></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"large">Interval notation:</td>
			<td class=3D"large">[1, 2)</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20


<h2>More Examples</h2>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example 1: "The Nothing Over $10 Sale"<br></h3>=20

	<p>That means <b>up to and including</b> $10.</p>=20
	<p>And it is fair to say all prices are more than $0,00.</p>=20
	<p>As an <b>inequality</b> we show this as:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger">Price =E2=89=A4 10 and Price &gt; 0</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center">In fact we could combine that into:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger">0 &lt; Price =E2=89=A4 10</p>=20
	<p>On the <b>number line</b> it looks like this:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/sets/images/int=
erval-0-10.svg" alt=3D"(0, 10]" height=3D"57" width=3D"221"></p>=20
	<p>And using <b>interval notation</b> it is simply:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><span class=3D"larger">(0, 10]</span></p>=20
	<div class=3D"gap"></div>
</div>=20

<div class=3D"gap"></div>

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example 2: "Competitors must be between 14 and 18"</h3>=20

	<p>So 14 is included, and "being 18" goes all the way up to (but not inclu=
ding) 19.</p>=20
	<p>As an inequality it looks like this:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger">14 =E2=89=A4 Age &lt; 19</p>=20
	<p>On the number line it looks like this:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/sets/images/int=
erval-14-19.svg" alt=3D"[14, 19)" height=3D"58" width=3D"276"></p>=20
	<p>And using interval notation it is simply:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger">[14, 19)</p>=20
</div>=20

<p><i>Isn't it funny how we measure age quite differently from anything els=
e? We stay 18 right up until the moment we are fully 19. We don't <a href=
=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/rounding-numbers.html">round up</a> to 19 fr=
om 18=C2=BD onwards</i>.</p>=20


<h2>Open or Closed</h2>=20

<p>The terms "Open" and "Closed" are sometimes used when the end value is i=
ncluded or not:</p>=20
<div class=3D"simple">

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td class=3D"large">Interval</td>
			<td class=3D"large">Inequality</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">&nbsp;</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"larger">(a, b)</td>
			<td class=3D"larger">a &lt; x &lt; b</td>
			<td>an open interval</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"larger">[a, b)</td>
			<td class=3D"larger">a =E2=89=A4 x &lt; b</td>
			<td>closed on left, open on right</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"larger"> (a, b]</td>
			<td class=3D"larger">a &lt; x =E2=89=A4 b</td>
			<td>open on left, closed on right</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"larger"> [a, b]</td>
			<td class=3D"larger">a =E2=89=A4 x =E2=89=A4 b</td>
			<td>a closed interval</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20

<p>These are intervals of finite length. We also have intervals of infinite=
 length.</p>=20


<h2>To Infinity (but not beyond!)</h2>=20

<p>We often use <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/infinity.html=
">Infinity</a> in interval notation.</p>=20
<p>Infinity is <b>not a real number</b>, in this case it just means "contin=
uing on ..."</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: x greater than, or equal to, 3:</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center"><span class=3D"large">[3, +=E2=88=9E)</span></p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/sets/images/int=
erval-3-inf.svg" alt=3D"[3, infinity)" height=3D"55" width=3D"157"></p>=20
</div>=20

<p>Note that we use the round bracket with infinity, because we don't reach=
 it!</p>=20
<p>There are 4 possible "infinite ends":</p>=20
<div class=3D"simple">

	<table class=3D"center" style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td class=3D"large">Interval</td>
			<td class=3D"large">Inequality</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">&nbsp;</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"large">(a, +=E2=88=9E)</td>
			<td class=3D"large">x &gt; a</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">greater than a</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"large">[a, +=E2=88=9E)</td>
			<td class=3D"large">x =E2=89=A5 a</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">greater than or equal to a</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"large">(-=E2=88=9E, a)</td>
			<td class=3D"large">x &lt; a</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">less than a</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"large">(-=E2=88=9E, a]</td>
			<td class=3D"large">x =E2=89=A4 a</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center;">less than or equal to a</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20

<p>We can show <b>no limits</b> by using this notation: <span class=3D"larg=
e">(-=E2=88=9E, +=E2=88=9E)</span></p>=20


<h2>Two Intervals</h2>=20

<p>We can have two (or more) intervals.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: x =E2=89=A4 2 or x &gt; 3</h3>=20

	<p>On the number line it looks like this:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/sets/images/int=
erval-to-2-3-inf.svg" alt=3D"two intervals" height=3D"55" width=3D"293"></p=
>=20
	<p>And interval notation looks like this:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center large">(-=E2=88=9E, 2] U (3, +=E2=88=9E)</p>=20
	<p>We used a "U" to mean Union (the joining together of two <a href=3D"htt=
ps://www.mathsisfun.com/sets/sets-introduction.html">sets</a>).</p>=20
</div><br>
<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td>=20

<p><i>Note: be careful with inequalities like that one.<br>
Don't try to join it into one inequality:</i></p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">2 =E2=89=A5 x &gt; 3 <img src=3D"https://www.math=
sisfun.com/images/style/no.svg" alt=3D"Not" style=3D"vertical-align: middle=
;" height=3D"30" width=3D"30"> wrong!</p>=20
<p><i>that doesn't make sense (you can't be less than 2<br>
and greater than 3 at the same time).</i></p></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20


<h2>Union and Intersection</h2>=20

<p>We just saw how to join two sets using "Union" (and the symbol <b>=E2=88=
=AA</b>).</p>=20
<p>There is also "Intersection" which means "has to be in both". <i>Think "=
where do they overlap?".</i></p>=20
<p>The Intersection symbol is an upside down "U" like this: <b>=E2=88=A9</b=
></p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: (-=E2=88=9E, 6] =E2=88=A9&nbsp;(1, =E2=88=9E)</h3>=20

	<p>The first interval goes up to (and including) 6</p>=20
	<p>The second interval goes from (but not including) 1 onwards.</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/sets/images/int=
erval-intersection.svg" alt=3D"interval intersection" height=3D"169" width=
=3D"258"></p>=20
	<p>The <b>Intersection</b> (or overlap) of those two sets goes from 1 to 6=
 (not including 1, including 6):</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center large">(1, 6]</p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"gap"></div>


<h2>Conclusion</h2>=20

<ul class=3D"large">=20
	<li>An Interval is all the numbers between two given numbers</li>=20
	<li>It is important to show if the beginning and end number are included</=
li>=20
	<li>There are three main ways to show intervals: Inequalities, The Number =
Line and Interval Notation</li>=20
</ul>=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>

